metadata.name: Aging and Forgotten #57
metadata.description:
"Aging and Forgotten" is my tribute to the transience of technology and life. In this exhibit, I bring together a collection of discarded technological devices and symbols of aging and death, such as skulls and bones. My goal is to create a powerful commentary on the impermanence of all things and the parallel between the aging of technology and the aging of people. Through the combination of technology and the human, I invite viewers to reflect on their own experiences of aging, loss, and the passage of time. With "Aging and Forgotten," I aim to challenge viewers to consider the impact of our rapidly advancing technology and the ultimate fate of all things, both human and technological.

- look for the gold mode
- press p to export png
- press s to export svg

metadata.name: Plottable Art Deco #4
metadata.description:
Initially made for #genuary 2023, JAN. 20 Art Deco prompt, a fxhash generator was generalized. It can yield various properties including x and y mirroring,

Meant to be plotted with a gold gel pen on a A4 dark blue paper.

"Introducing 'Plottable Art Deco', created for #genuary2023's Art Deco prompt. This fxhash generator is capable of producing unique properties such as x and y mirroring and other rare patterns, making every outcome truly one-of-a-kind. Designed to be plotted on A4 dark blue paper with a gold gel pen, this digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece.

Owning this NFT grants the right to plot or request a physical plot from the artist on https://greweb.me/plots/nft

The source code for this piece is available on GitHub at https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-artdeco, and is licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0.

metadata.name: Balance #13
metadata.description:
(This is not just about still images, it's about sound and processes)

Balance was born from the Genuary 2023 event and the FxHash proposal to mint one "prompt" of your choice.
The chosen one was the "Generative music" prompt as an excuse to be able to explore a little the sound world that I have abandoned many years ago.

Balance is an experimental generative and interactive work that has a process of almost 3 minutes that is repeated indefinitely. The work explores the sound as matter in relation to the visual, in search of a balance in terms of sensations. As we already know, the visual has an immediate impact, while the sound, we need to dedicate more time to it. At an interactive level, you can control some actions that can enrich or ruin :) the process.

The sound is strongly influenced by composers who use granular synthesis, such as Curtis Roads. The visual parallel is represented by movement and the use of glitch aesthetics.

-----------

Balance nace a partir del evento Genuary 2023 y la propuesta de FxHash de mintear un "prompt" a elección.
El elegido fue el prompt "Generative music" como excusa poder explorar un poco el mundo sonoro que tengo abandonado hace muchos años.

Balance es un trabajo experimental generativo e interactivo que tiene un proceso de casi 3 minutos que se vuelve a repetir indefinidamente. El trabajo explora el sonido como materia en relación a lo visual, en busca de un balance en terminos de sensaciones. Como ya sabemos, lo visual tiene un impacto inmedito, en cambio lo sonoro, necesitamos dedicarle más tiempo. A nivel interactivo, se pueden controlar algunas acciones que pueden enriquezer o arruinar :) el proceso.

Lo sonoro está fuertemente influnciado por los compositores que utilizan la sintesis granular como Curtis Roads. El paralelo visual está representado por el movimiento y luego la utilización de la estética glitch.


Interactivity Keys:

[Click] -> to sound ON / OFF (remove text SOUND OFF) (be carefull if you use headphones, check levels)
(By policy, in browsers, all sounds start off muted until users interact)
[1 or Q] -> sound ON / OFF (remove text SOUND OFF) (be carefull if you use headphones, check levels)
[2 or W] -> smooth fx ON/OFF.
[3 or E] -> loop/noLoop - Play/Pause animation and freeze sound.
[4 or R] -> Glitch cutting.
[5 or T] -> Add Colors, glitch cutting and Notes at your own risk :) 
[6 or Y] -> (remove all texts)  
[7 or A] -> Restart with sound ON

metadata.name: Quadz #84
metadata.description:
Quadz is my first fxhash project which continues my exploration of creating visual designs based on polygons. Fxhash allowed me to develop a new take on the theme by generating polygon patterns based on rule-based randomization and p5js quad polygons. 

Quadz is composed of five layouts and three color palettes. 

Color Palettes:
- Red 
- Monochrome, light & dark 
- Turquoise

Layouts:
- Single Quad Small & Large
- Diagonal Quad from Two to Four Directions
- Four Diagonal Quads over Single Quad
- Two by Two Grid with Bg Colors
- Three by Three Grid, inspired by Vera Molnár 

Click on the image to save 1400x1400 png.

Thank you to Lisa Orth for the help with the responsive center image CSS.

Created By: lukaszgraphz
Twitter: https://twitter.com/lukasz_x2

Art: August 2022
Created with p5js
CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Pinceau #97
metadata.description:
An examination of using generative brush strokes to emulate real life paintings.

The result of each output is determined by a number of factors:
- selection from 21 different palettes
- brush transparency levels
- scale factor 
- "chaos level" - determines how far off the given path any the brush strokes of any given piece decide to go.

More info and additional test mints can be found in this thread:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1469083325881106440

metadata.name: Inefficient Ways of Independence #3
metadata.description:
"Inefficient Ways of Independence" is a thought - provoking artwork that explores the relationship between technology and the human experience.

The piece features a collection of iconic symbols of old technology, such as closed - circuit TV cameras, floppy disks, and vintage Mac computers, coupled together by a flow of particles.

The use of human body parts or heads adds a personal touch to the work, highlighting the intimate connection between the individual and technology.

The title "Inefficient Ways of Independence" serves as a commentary on our dependence on technology and the way that it has changed over time.

It also raises questions about our relationship with technology and the limitations that it can impose.

The piece invites the viewer to consider how technology has shaped our lives and to reflect on the consequences of our reliance on it.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT

metadata.name: fields, wireframes #87
metadata.description:
The second part of our generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022

metadata.name: Plottable Field (8 frames) #343
metadata.description:
'Field' explores the realm of noise field distortions through many different primitives: 15 unique distributions, 16 possible inks, and many kinds of distortions, ink combinations, and animations,...

A SVG file can be exported (right-click save) to plot the 8 frames of this animation on a A4 paper. This is a "plot loop". The physical piece is displayed as aesthetics 4x2 grid of the frames.

You can enjoy the digital version that simulates ink effects. But also, thanks to the utility token decoupling, get a physical one: the digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their materials and ship to collectors – as long as NFT is owned at request time.

metadata.name: SCHNEEWALD #116
metadata.description:
SCHNEEWALD is the second release in a row of about 12 tree/flower generative art works, which have come together over the last 10 years.

This project explores an approach to trees with snow using a recursive algorithm and includes Three traits: a density layer for the amount of trees and another layer for the amount snow and a third for how strong the branches bend.

Rendering progress indicated on the top left border
Press [s] in live view to download a high resolution png

Artist notes:
Since I moved to Wandlitz, north of Berlin, in the middle of the "Naturpark Barnim" (https://www.barnim-naturpark.de/), in 2003,
I've done a lot of exploring nearby nature. In addition to the beautiful lake and heath landscapes, I fell in love with the wild acacia forests. These strange trees, sometimes more like huge wild grasses, grow so wildly into each other.

I experienced it in all sorts of seasonal change, packed with snow is definitely among the most amazing! 

While playing around with different branching system code snippets, a more and more complex image composition came together. The final script for this project on fx(hash) was finally given more randomness for a wider range of different outputs and an additional random grain filter.

Project link: https://e-art.co/project/schneewald/

Many thanks to jesse (jbird) for the good collaboration, which ultimately made it possible to get this work released.
